      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_aldrovandi_7",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_monstrorum_historia_aldrovandi"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Quali siano i nomi, la natura, il comportamento e l'alimentazione di questo animale, è stato ampiamente discusso nello studio sui quadrupedi digitati. Rimane solo da aggiungere quanto dice in proposito il Paré, e da proporre un'immagine da poter osservare, che non era ancora disponibile al tempo del precedente volume. Ebbene, il Paré afferma che questo animale viene chiamato haut, ha le dimensioni di un cercopiteco, ma la testa e il volto somigliano a quelli di un bambino. Quando viene catturato si lamenta e tira fuori dal petto profondi sospiri, come un uomo ansioso e sofferente. Le sue zampe sono munite di tre artigli; scala gli alberi e trascorre lassù più tempo che a terra. Cammina così lentamente che, nell'atto di allungare le zampe, tocca quasi il suolo con il ventre. In quindici giorni non copre la distanza di un tiro di pietra; una volta che è salito su un albero, vi trascorre due giorni, e non accelera i movimenti neanche quando è minacciato o in pericolo.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Capitolo 3: il mostro in generale",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_mostro_aldrovandi_3"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_topsell_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_history_of_four_footed_beasts"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "This beast or rather Monster is bred among the Indians, having a treble row of teeth beneath and above, whose greatness, roughness, and feet are like a Lyon, his face and ears like unto a mans, his eyes gray, and colour red, his tail like the tail of a Scorpion, of the earth, armed with a sting, casting forth sharp pointed quils; his voyce like the voyce of a small Trumpet or Pipe, being in course as swift as a Hart; his wildeness such as can never be tamed, and his appetite is especially to the flesh of man. His body like the body of a Lyon, being very apt both to leap and to run,  so as no distance or space doth hinder him [...].",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Volume 1",
        "chapter: Of the Mantichora"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_manticore_topsell"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_bible_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_bible"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "In quel tempo c'erano sulla terra i giganti, e ci furono anche in seguito, quando i figli di Dio si unirono alle figlie degli uomini, ed ebbero da loro dei figli. Questi sono gli uomini potenti che, fin dai tempi antichi, sono stati famosi.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Genesi 6:4",
        "verse 4"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_giant_bible"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:genesis_sphinx_apollodoro",
      "@type": "beast:Genesis",
      "beast:hasGenesisDescription": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "Daughter of Echidna and Typhon"
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "sent to Thebes as an instrument of divine punishment."
        }
      ],
      "beast:involvesParent": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:myth_echidna"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:myth_typhon"
        }
      ],
      "beast:isGenesisOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_sphinx_apollodoro"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_erodoto_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_erodoto_histories"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "There is also another sacred bird called the phoenix which I did not myself see except in painting, for in truth he comes to them very rarely, at intervals, as the people of Heliopolis say, of five hundred years; and these say that he comes regularly when his father dies; and if he be like the painting, he is of this size and nature, that is to say, some of his feathers are of gold colour and others red, and in outline and size he is as nearly as possible like an eagle. This bird they say (but I cannot believe the story) contrives as follows: - setting forth from Arabia he conveys his father, they say, to the temple of the Sun (Helios) plastered up in myrrh, and buries him in the temple of the Sun; and he conveys him thus: - he forms first an egg of myrrh as large as he is able to carry, and then he makes trial of carrying it, and when he has made trial sufficiently, then he hollows out the egg and places his father within it and plasters over with other myrrh that part of the egg where he hollowed it out to put his father in, and when his father is laid in it, it proves (they say) to be of the same weight as it was; and after he has plastered it up, he conveys the whole to Egypt to the temple of the Sun. Thus they say that this bird does.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Book II",
        "paragraph 73"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_phoenix_erodoto"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:source_camera_giganti",
      "@type": "beast:VisualArtwork",
      "beast:containsInterpretation": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_giant_camera_dei_giganti"
      },
      "beast:wasInfluencedBy": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:source_biblioteca"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:source_ovidius_metamorphoses"
        }
      ],
      "dcterms:created": {
        "@type": "http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#gYear",
        "@value": "1532/1535"
      },
      "dcterms:title": "Camera dei Giganti",
