        "@value": "https://www.centropalazzote.it/camera-dei-giganti/"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_minotaur_dante",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_dante_inferno"
      },
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SchizomorphicStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesArchetype": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:archetype_guardian_hell"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:archetype_violence"
        }
      ],
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": [
        {
          "@id": "beast:CatamorphicSymbol"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beast:TeriomorphicSymbol"
        }
      ],
      "beast:hasTextualReference": {
        "@id": "beastiary:citation_dante_inferno_1"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_minotaur"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The Minotaur in Dante functions as a predominantly theriomorphic symbol of chaotic animality. His self-biting and self-lacerating rage exemplify the schema of devouring jaws turned inward: the beast consumes itself, becoming an image of violence that is both destructive and self-destructive. At the same time, Dante intensifies the symbol through a catamorphic register. The creature is located in the descending geography of Hell and is linked to the fall from reason into brute impulse."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_ovid_met_5",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_ovidius_metamorphoses"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Now the entwined bodies of the two were joined together, and one form covered both. Just as when someone grafts a twig into the bark, they see both grow joined together, and develop as one, so when they were mated together in a close embrace, they were not two, but a two-fold form, so that they could not be called male or female, and seemed neither or either.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Book IV",
        "verses 373-379"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_hermaphrodite_ovidius"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:source_greek_natural_history",
      "@type": "beast:Tradition"
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_hermaphrodite_plato",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
