        "@value": "Hippogriff"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_ende_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_unendliche_geschichte"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "And beside this pillar, as Atreyu now saw, an enormous sphinx was sitting motionless in the moonlight. The forepaws, on which she was propped, were those of a lion, the hindquarters were those of a bull; on her back she bore the wings of an eagle, and her face was that of a human woman - in form at any rate, for the expression was far from human. I was hard to tell whether this face was smiling or whether it expressed deep grief or utter indifference. After looking at it for some time, Atreyu seemed to see abysmal wickedness and cruelty, but a moment later he had to correct his impression, for he found only unruffled calm. [...] Then the right-hand pillar came into Atreyu's view. And there, in the same posture, sat a second sphinx. The enormous body shimmered like liquid silver in the moonlight. She seemed to be staring fixedly at the first, just as the first was gazing fixedly at her.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Chapter 6",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_sphinx_ende"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:ability_accumulate_treasures",
      "@type": "beast:Ability",
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:MysticalStructure"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:NocturnalRegime"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "The behavioral tendency to collect and guard valuable objects such as gold or precious stones."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "Trolls tend to accumulate treasures because they are attracted to the materiality of things. It represents a declination of Durand's mystical structures that focus on sensory attachment."
        }
      ],
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Treasure hoarding"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:myth_achelous",
      "@type": "beast:MythologicalFigure",
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Achelous"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_rowling_6",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_fantastic_beasts"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Probably the most famous of all magical beasts, dragons are among the most difficult to hide. The female is generally larger and more aggressive than the male, though neither should be approached by any but highly skilled and trained wizards. Dragon hide, blood, heart, liver, and horn all have highly magical properties, but dragon eggs are defined as Class A Non-Tradeable Goods. There are ten breeds of dragon, though these have been known to interbreed on occasion, producing rare hybrids.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_dragon_rowling_fantastic"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_esiodo_2",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_teogonia"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "A Forci Ceto generò le Graie dalle belle guance, / canute dalla nascita, che chiamano Graie / gli dèi immortali e gli uomini che camminano sulla terra, / Penfredo dal bel peplo e Enio dal peplo di croco, / e le Gorgoni, che abitano al di là dell'illustre Oceano, / al limite verso la Notte, dove sono le Esperidi dalla voce sonora, / Stenno e Euriale e Medusa che soffrì sciagure: / questa era mortale, mentre immortali e eternamente giovani / le altre due; ma accanto a lei sola giacque l'Azzurrochiomato / sul tenero prato e tra i fiori di primavera. / E quando Perseo le tagliò la testa, / saltarono fuori il grande Crisaore e il cavallo Pegaso.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Lines 270-281",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_medusa_esiodo"
      }
    },
