      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_snake"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The serpent of Mars is a giant, fire-eyed, venom-swollen guardian with triple rows of teeth that devours Cadmus's men; it is a pure teriomorphic chaos-monster."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:habitat_desert",
      "@type": "beast:RealWorldPlace",
      "beast:habitatCategory": {
        "@id": "beast:Terrestrial"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "An arid expanse of sand and barren ground."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Desert"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_aberdeen_5",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_aberdeen_bestiary"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "The monoceros is a monster the body of a horse, the feet of an elephant and a tail very like that of a deer. A magnificent, marvellous horn projects from the middle of its forehead, four feet in length, so sharp that whatever it strikes is easily pierced with the blow. No living monoceros has ever come into man's hands, and while it can be killed, it cannot be captured.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Folio 15r",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_unicorn_aberdeen"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_shrek_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_shrek"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "It's the world that seems to have a problem with me. People take one look at me and go, 'Ah! Help! Run! Big, stupid, ugly ogre!' They judge me before they even know me.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_ogre_shrek"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:genesis_hermaphrodite_ovidius",
      "@type": "beast:Genesis",
      "beast:hasGenesisDescription": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "Child of Hermes and Aphrodite"
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "originally a male youth of great beauty. Fused into a single dual-sexed body with the nymph Salmacis after she embraced him in her pool and prayed never to be parted from him."
        }
      ],
      "beast:involvesParent": [
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:myth_aphrodite"
        },
        {
          "@id": "beastiary:myth_hermes"
        }
      ],
      "beast:isGenesisOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_hermaphrodite_ovidius"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:archetype_shameful_offspring",
      "@type": "beast:Archetype",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A creature born of transgression and condemned to concealment, embodying the social and moral need to hide the consequences of forbidden desire."
      },
      "beast:relatedTo": {
        "@id": "beastiary:archetype_abandoned_child"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Shameful Offspring"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_pharsalia_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_pharsalia"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Quel suol però sí sterile, e que' campi / Di niun bene fecondi, un tosco atroce / Concepiscono in lor dalle corrotte Gocciole di Medusa [...] Ivi dispiega [...] e'l Basilisco horrendo / (Che Sibili tramanda, onde rimane / Ogni serpe atterrito, e pria che sparga / Il veleno, dà morte) il serpentino / Volgo da sé rimove, e in vuote arene / Solo il regno ritien.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Book IX",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_basilisk_lucano"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:habitat_chamber_of_secrets",
      "@type": "beast:ImaginaryPlace",
      "beast:hasOriginContext": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_harry_potter_book_2"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A vast underground chamber hidden beneath Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, built by Salazar Slytherin in the 10th century to conceal his basilisk."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Chamber of Secrets"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_satyr_statue",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:additionalAbility": {
        "@id": "beastiary:ability_play_foot_castanet"
      },
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_satyr_statue"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_satyr"
      },
      "beast:removedPart": {
        "@id": "beastiary:part_two_horns"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:ability_self_renewal",
      "@type": "beast:Ability",
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SyntheticStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:CyclicalSymbol"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:NocturnalRegime"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "Self-renewal is the cyclical symbol itself: death reintegrated as a necessary phase of an incessant movement in which every ending is the prelude to rebirth."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "The capacity to regenerate, rejuvenate, or be reborn, often cyclically."
        }
      ],
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Self-renewal"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_sphinx_plinio",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_naturalis_historia"
      },
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SchizomorphicStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesArchetype": {
        "@id": "beastiary:archetype_exotic_marvel"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:SpectacularSymbol"
      },
      "beast:hasTextualReference": {
        "@id": "beastiary:citation_plinio_1"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_sphinx"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Pliny's sphinx carries the spectacular symbolism of the luminous, solar creature observed as a marvel, its presence belonging to the register of clear vision and heroic light."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_poem_hermaphroditus",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_poem_hermaphroditus"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Where between sleep and life some brief space is, / With love like gold bound round about the head, / Sex to sweet sex with lips and limbs is wed, / Turning the fruitful feud of hers and his / To the waste wedlock of a sterile kiss.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Verse 17-21",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_hermaphrodite_swinburne"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:ability_poisonous",
      "@type": "beast:Ability",
      "beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure": {
        "@id": "beast:SchizomorphicStructure"
      },
      "beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol": {
        "@id": "beast:TeriomorphicSymbol"
      },
      "beast:isGovernedBy": {
        "@id": "beast:DiurnalRegime"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "Aggressive natural weaponry expresses the teriomorphic 'enemy symbol' of feral chaos and the bestial threat of the striking attack."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "The creature produces or secretes a toxic substance capable of harming or killing through bite, touch, or breath."
        }
      ],
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Venomous"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:diet_man_eater",
      "beast:dietCategory": {
        "@id": "beast:Carnivorous"
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "A carnivorous diet directed especially at human flesh; the creature preys on people by preference, beyond ordinary predation on animals."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Man eater"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_tolkien_2",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_lotr"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Trolls they were, but filled with the evil will of their master: a fell race, strong, agile, fierce and cunning, but harder than stone. Unlike the older race of the Twilight they could endure the Sun, so long as the will of Sauron held sway over them. They spoke little, and the only tongue that they knew was the Black Speech of Barad-dûr.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Appendix F",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_troll_tolkien"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:archetype_violence",
      "@type": "beast:Archetype",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Brute destructive force and aggression."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Violence"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_physiologus_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_physiologus"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "It had the face (or fore-part) of a lion and the hinder parts of an ant. Its father eats flesh, but its mother grains. If they engender the ant-lion, they engender a thing of two natures, such that it cannot eat flesh because of the nature of its mother, nor grains because of the nature of its father. It perishes, therefore, because it has no nutriment.",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_antlion_physiologus"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:int_anomaly_aldrovandi_1",
      "@type": "beast:Interpretation",
      "beast:appearsIn": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_monstrorum_historia_aldrovandi"
      },
      "beast:hasTextualReference": {
        "@id": "beastiary:citation_aldrovandi_4"
      },
      "beast:ofCreature": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_hairy_girl"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_ende_2",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_unendliche_geschichte"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Luckdragons are among the strangest animals in Fantastica. They bear no resemblance to ordinary dragons, which look like loathsome snakes and live in deep caves, diffusing a noxious stench and guarding some real or imaginary treasure. [...] Luckdragons are creatures of air, warmth, and pure joy. Despite their great size, they are as light as a summer cloud, and consequently need no wings for flying. They swim in the air of heaven as fish swim in water. Seen from the earth, they look like slow lightning flashes. The most amazing thing about them is their song. Their voice sounds like the golden note of a large bell, and when they speak softly the bell seems to be ringing in the distance. Anyone who has heard this sound will remember it as long as he lives and tell his grandchildren about it. But the luckdragon Atreyu saw could hardly have been in a mood for singing. His long, graceful body with its pearly, pink-and-white scales hung tangled and twisted in the great spider web. His bristling fangs, his thick, luxuriant mane, and the fringes on his tail and limbs were all caught in the sticky ropes. He could hardly move. The eyeballs in his lionlike head glistened ruby-red. The splendid beast bled from many wounds, for there was something else, something very big, that descended like a dark cloud on the dragon's white body. It rose and fell, rose and fell, all the while changing its shape. Sometimes it resembled a gigantic long-legged spider with many fiery eyes and a fat body encased in shaggy black hair; then it became a great hand with long claws that tried to crush the luckdragon, and in the next moment it changed to a giant scorpion, piercing its unfortunate victim with its venomous sting.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Chapter 4",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_dragon_ende"
      }
    },
