    {
      "@id": "beastiary:etymology_scorpion",
      "@type": "beast:Etymology",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The word \"'scorpion' originates from the Latin term 'scorpionem', which is derived from the Greek word 'skorpios'. This Greek term is related to the Proto-Indo-European root 'sker-', meaning to cut or to shear."
      },
      "beast:hasRootTerm": {
        "@language": "la",
        "@value": "Scorpionem"
      },
      "beast:isEtymologyOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:creature_scorpion"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_plinio_6",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_naturalis_historia"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Goats use ivy and a diet consisting mostly of crabs thrown up from the sea [to cure themselves of sickness]. Mucianus has described a case of this animal's cleverness seen by himself - two goats coming in opposite directions met on a very narrow bridge, and as the narrow space did not permit them to turn round and the length did not allow of backing blindly on the scanty passageway with a rushing torrent flowing threateningly below, one of them lay down and so the other one passed over, treading on top of it... according to Archelaus they breathe through the ears, not the nostrils, and are never free from fever: this is perhaps the reason why they are more high-spirited than sheep and hotter in coupling. It is said that goats can see by night as well as they can in the daytime, and that consequently a diet of goat's liver restores sight to persons suffering from what is called night-blindness.They say that she-goats in the pastures when the sun is setting do not look at one another but He down with their backs to each other, though at other times of the day they lie facing each other and take notice of one another. Their bite kills a tree; they make an olive tree barren even by licking it, and for this reason they are not offered in sacrifice to Minerva. Herds of goats also have their special reputation for cheese, in the case of fresh cheese especially when smoke increases its flavor, as with the supremely desirable cheese made in the city itself; for the cheese of the Gallic goats always has a strong medicinal taste. The horn or hair of she-goats, when burnt, is said to keep serpents away, and the ash from the horn, whether taken in drink or applied, to be efficacious for their bites; as are also draughts of their milk with taminian grapes, or of their urine with squill vinegar; so too an application of goat cheese with marjoram, or of goat suet with wax. Thousands of remedies besides from the goat are given in prescriptions, as will be pointed out; this is surprising to me, because it is said never to be free from fever..",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": [
        "Book VIII",
        "paragraph 41"
      ],
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_goat_plinio"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:archetype_vice",
      "@type": "beast:Archetype",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The embodiment of a moral failing or sinful disposition - a creature that personifies a specific human vice such as pride, lust, or wrath, serving as an allegorical warning against that failing."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Vice"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:function_guide",
      "@type": "beast:NarrativeFunction",
      "beast:hasMeaning": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The creature leads, accompanies, or directs the protagonist, offering aid or direction on their path."
      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Guide"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_paré_7",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_monstres_prodiges"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "Questo mostro marino, con la testa, la criniera e il davanti equino fu visto nel mare Oceano; il suo ritratto fu portato a Roma al papa allora regnante.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Capitolo 34: Ora parliamo di mostri marini",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_mostro_paré_5"
      }
    },
