      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Firenze and his kind read the future in the stars, positioning the centaur as a creature of celestial vision and solar clarity; their role as guides and protectors of the Forbidden Forest is grounded in this spectacular, sky-watching wisdom rather than in bestial appetite."
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "beastiary:citation_maier_1",
      "@type": "beast:Citation",
      "beast:extractedFrom": {
        "@id": "beastiary:source_atalanta_fugiens"
      },
      "beast:hasPassageText": "For Sphinx is a certain kind of monster most obscure to the Thebans, propounding riddles, nor only to them, but as before to the Egyptians, so after all others to those that aspire to art, and watches in the Philosophers books as before the gates of Thebes; if any man can pass by the monster, he suffers no evil by him, but he that through presumption of mind or wit endeavors to resolve his riddles, and cannot perform, acquires his own destruction, that is, grief to the heart, and damage to his affairs by error in this work.",
      "beast:hasSequenceIdentifier": "Emblem 39",
      "beast:isTextualReferenceOf": {
        "@id": "beastiary:int_sphinx_maier"
      }
    },
